::: {#slice-content}
::: {#section-4.7 .section}
### [4.7.](#section-4.7){.section-number .selfRef} [Slice Content](#name-slice-content){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice-content}

A `Slice Content` contains all Line elements part of the
`Slice`.[¶](#section-4.7-1){.pilcrow}

Depending on the configuration, Line elements are ordered by Plane then
by row (YCbCr) or by row then by Plane
(RGB).[¶](#section-4.7-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.7-3}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-pseudocode}
pseudocode                                                    | type
--------------------------------------------------------------|-----
SliceContent( ) {                                             |
    if (colorspace_type == 0) {                               |
        for (p = 0; p < primary_color_count; p++) {           |
            for (y = 0; y < plane_pixel_height[ p ]; y++) {   |
                Line( p, y )                                  |
            }                                                 |
        }                                                     |
    } else if (colorspace_type == 1) {                        |
        for (y = 0; y < slice_pixel_height; y++) {            |
            for (p = 0; p < primary_color_count; p++) {       |
                Line( p, y )                                  |
            }                                                 |
        }                                                     |
    }                                                         |
}                                                             |
```

[¶](#section-4.7-3){.pilcrow}
:::

::: {#primary-color-count}
::: {#section-4.7.1 .section}
#### [4.7.1.](#section-4.7.1){.section-number .selfRef} [`primary_color_count`](#name-primary_color_count){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-primary_color_count}

`primary_color_count` is defined as the
following:[¶](#section-4.7.1-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.7.1-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    1 + ( chroma_planes ? 2 : 0 ) + ( extra_plane ? 1 : 0 )

[¶](#section-4.7.1-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#plane-pixel-height}
::: {#section-4.7.2 .section}
#### [4.7.2.](#section-4.7.2){.section-number .selfRef} [`plane_pixel_height`](#name-plane_pixel_height){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-plane_pixel_height}

`plane_pixel_height[ p ]` is the height in pixels of Plane p of the
`Slice`. It is defined as the following:[¶](#section-4.7.2-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.7.2-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    chroma_planes == 1 && (p == 1 || p == 2)
        ? ceil(slice_pixel_height / (1 << log2_v_chroma_subsample))
        : slice_pixel_height

[¶](#section-4.7.2-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-pixel-height}
::: {#section-4.7.3 .section}
#### [4.7.3.](#section-4.7.3){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_pixel_height`](#name-slice_pixel_height){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_pixel_height}

`slice_pixel_height` is the height in pixels of the Slice. It is defined
as the following:[¶](#section-4.7.3-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.7.3-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    floor(
            ( slice_y + slice_height )
            * slice_pixel_height
            / num_v_slices
        ) - slice_pixel_y.

[¶](#section-4.7.3-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-pixel-y}
::: {#section-4.7.4 .section}
#### [4.7.4.](#section-4.7.4){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_pixel_y`](#name-slice_pixel_y){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_pixel_y}

`slice_pixel_y` is the Slice vertical position in pixels. It is defined
as the following:[¶](#section-4.7.4-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.7.4-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    floor( slice_y * frame_pixel_height / num_v_slices )

[¶](#section-4.7.4-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#line}
::: {#section-4.8 .section}
### [4.8.](#section-4.8){.section-number .selfRef} [Line](#name-line){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-line}

A `Line` is a list of the Sample Differences (relative to the predictor)
of primary color components. The pseudocode below describes the contents
of the `Line`.[¶](#section-4.8-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.8-2}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-pseudocode}
pseudocode                                                    | type
--------------------------------------------------------------|-----
Line( p, y ) {                                                |
    if (colorspace_type == 0) {                               |
        for (x = 0; x < plane_pixel_width[ p ]; x++) {        |
            sample_difference[ p ][ y ][ x ]                  | sd
        }                                                     |
    } else if (colorspace_type == 1) {                        |
        for (x = 0; x < slice_pixel_width; x++) {             |
            sample_difference[ p ][ y ][ x ]                  | sd
        }                                                     |
    }                                                         |
}                                                             |
```

[¶](#section-4.8-2){.pilcrow}
:::

::: {#plane-pixel-width}
::: {#section-4.8.1 .section}
#### [4.8.1.](#section-4.8.1){.section-number .selfRef} [`plane_pixel_width`](#name-plane_pixel_width){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-plane_pixel_width}

`plane_pixel_width[ p ]` is the width in pixels of Plane p of the
`Slice`. It is defined as the following:[¶](#section-4.8.1-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.8.1-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    chroma_planes == 1 && (p == 1 || p == 2)
        ? ceil( slice_pixel_width / (1 << log2_h_chroma_subsample) )
        : slice_pixel_width.

[¶](#section-4.8.1-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-pixel-width}
::: {#section-4.8.2 .section}
#### [4.8.2.](#section-4.8.2){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_pixel_width`](#name-slice_pixel_width){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_pixel_width}

`slice_pixel_width` is the width in pixels of the Slice. It is defined
as the following:[¶](#section-4.8.2-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.8.2-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    floor(
            ( slice_x + slice_width )
            * slice_pixel_width
            / num_h_slices
        ) - slice_pixel_x

[¶](#section-4.8.2-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-pixel-x}
::: {#section-4.8.3 .section}
#### [4.8.3.](#section-4.8.3){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_pixel_x`](#name-slice_pixel_x){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_pixel_x}

`slice_pixel_x` is the Slice horizontal position in pixels. It is
defined as the following:[¶](#section-4.8.3-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.8.3-2 .artwork .art-text .alignLeft .art-ascii-art}
    floor( slice_x * frame_pixel_width / num_h_slices )

[¶](#section-4.8.3-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#sample-difference}
::: {#section-4.8.4 .section}
#### [4.8.4.](#section-4.8.4){.section-number .selfRef} [`sample_difference`](#name-sample_difference){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-sample_difference}

`sample_difference[ p ][ y ][ x ]` is the Sample Difference for Sample
at Plane `p`, y position `y`, and x position `x`. The Sample value is
computed based on median predictor and context described in [Section
3.2](#samples){.xref}.[¶](#section-4.8.4-1){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-footer}
::: {#section-4.9 .section}
### [4.9.](#section-4.9){.section-number .selfRef} [Slice Footer](#name-slice-footer){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice-footer}

A `Slice Footer` provides information about Slice size and (optionally)
parity. The pseudocode below describes the contents of the
`Slice Footer`.[¶](#section-4.9-1){.pilcrow}

Note: `Slice Footer` is always byte
aligned.[¶](#section-4.9-2){.pilcrow}

::: {#section-4.9-3}
``` {.sourcecode .lang-pseudocode}
pseudocode                                                    | type
--------------------------------------------------------------|-----
SliceFooter( ) {                                              |
    slice_size                                                | u(24)
    if (ec) {                                                 |
        error_status                                          | u(8)
        slice_crc_parity                                      | u(32)
    }                                                         |
}                                                             |
```

[¶](#section-4.9-3){.pilcrow}
:::

::: {#slice-size}
::: {#section-4.9.1 .section}
#### [4.9.1.](#section-4.9.1){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_size`](#name-slice_size){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_size}

`slice_size` indicates the size of the Slice in
bytes.[¶](#section-4.9.1-1){.pilcrow}

Note: this allows finding the start of Slices before previous Slices
have been fully decoded and allows parallel decoding as well as error
resilience.[¶](#section-4.9.1-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#error-status}
::: {#section-4.9.2 .section}
#### [4.9.2.](#section-4.9.2){.section-number .selfRef} [`error_status`](#name-error_status){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-error_status}

`error_status` specifies the error
status.[¶](#section-4.9.2-1){.pilcrow}

[]{#name-the-definitions-for-error_s}

::: {#tableErrorStatus}
  value   error status
  ------- ---------------------------------------
  0       no error
  1       Slice contains a correctable error
  2       Slice contains an uncorrectable error
  Other   reserved for future use

  : [Table 16](#table-16){.selfRef}: [The definitions for `error_status`
  values.](#name-the-definitions-for-error_s){.selfRef}
:::
:::
:::

::: {#slice-crc-parity}
::: {#section-4.9.3 .section}
#### [4.9.3.](#section-4.9.3){.section-number .selfRef} [`slice_crc_parity`](#name-slice_crc_parity){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-slice_crc_parity}

`slice_crc_parity` is 32 bits that are chosen so that the Slice as a
whole has a CRC remainder of 0.[¶](#section-4.9.3-1){.pilcrow}

This is equivalent to storing the CRC remainder in the 32-bit
parity.[¶](#section-4.9.3-2){.pilcrow}

The CRC generator polynomial used is the standard IEEE CRC polynomial
(0x104C11DB7) with initial value 0, without pre-inversion, and without
post-inversion.[¶](#section-4.9.3-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::
:::

::: {#restrictions}
::: {#section-5 .section}
## [5.](#section-5){.section-number .selfRef} [Restrictions](#name-restrictions){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-restrictions}

To ensure that fast multithreaded decoding is possible, starting with
version 3 and if `frame_pixel_width * frame_pixel_height` is more than
101376, `slice_width * slice_height` [MUST]{.bcp14} be less or equal to
`num_h_slices * num_v_slices / 4`. Note: 101376 is the frame size in
pixels of a 352x288 frame also known as CIF (Common Intermediate Format)
frame size format.[¶](#section-5-1){.pilcrow}

For each Frame, each position in the Slice raster [MUST]{.bcp14} be
filled by one and only one Slice of the Frame (no missing Slice position
and no Slice overlapping).[¶](#section-5-2){.pilcrow}

For each Frame with a `keyframe` value of 0, each Slice [MUST]{.bcp14}
have the same value of `slice_x`, `slice_y`, `slice_width`, and
`slice_height` as a Slice in the previous
Frame.[¶](#section-5-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#security-considerations}
::: {#section-6 .section}
## [6.](#section-6){.section-number .selfRef} [Security Considerations](#name-security-considerations){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-security-considerations}

Like any other codec (such as \[[RFC6716](#RFC6716){.xref}\]), FFV1
should not be used with insecure ciphers or cipher modes that are
vulnerable to known plaintext attacks. Some of the header bits as well
as the padding are easily predictable.[¶](#section-6-1){.pilcrow}

Implementations of the FFV1 codec need to take appropriate security
considerations into account. Those related to denial of service are
outlined in [Section
2.1](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc4732#section-2.1){.relref} of
\[[RFC4732](#RFC4732){.xref}\]. It is extremely important for the
decoder to be robust against malicious payloads. Malicious payloads
[MUST NOT]{.bcp14} cause the decoder to overrun its allocated memory or
to take an excessive amount of resources to decode. An overrun in
allocated memory could lead to arbitrary code execution by an attacker.
The same applies to the encoder, even though problems in encoders are
typically rarer. Malicious video streams [MUST NOT]{.bcp14} cause the
encoder to misbehave because this would allow an attacker to attack
transcoding gateways. A frequent security problem in image and video
codecs is failure to check for integer overflows. An example is
allocating `frame_pixel_width * frame_pixel_height` in pixel count
computations without considering that the multiplication result may have
overflowed the range of the arithmetic type. The range coder could, if
implemented naively, read one byte over the end. The implementation
[MUST]{.bcp14} ensure that no read outside allocated and initialized
memory occurs.[¶](#section-6-2){.pilcrow}

None of the content carried in FFV1 is intended to be
executable.[¶](#section-6-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#multithreaded-decoder-implementation-suggestions}
::: {#appendix-A .section}
## [Appendix A.](#appendix-A){.section-number .selfRef} [Multithreaded Decoder Implementation Suggestions](#name-multithreaded-decoder-imple){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-multithreaded-decoder-imple}

This appendix is informative.[¶](#appendix-A-1){.pilcrow}

The FFV1 bitstream is parsable in two ways: in sequential order as
described in this document or with the pre-analysis of the footer of
each Slice. Each Slice footer contains a `slice_size` field so the
boundary of each Slice is computable without having to parse the Slice
content. That allows multithreading as well as independence of Slice
content (a bitstream error in a Slice header or Slice content has no
impact on the decoding of the other Slices).[¶](#appendix-A-2){.pilcrow}

After having checked the `keyframe` field, a decoder should parse
`slice_size` fields, from `slice_size` of the last Slice at the end of
the `Frame` up to `slice_size` of the first Slice at the beginning of
the `Frame` before parsing Slices, in order to have Slice boundaries. A
decoder may fall back on sequential order e.g., in case of a corrupted
`Frame` (e.g., frame size unknown or `slice_size` of Slices not
coherent) or if there is no possibility of seeking into the
stream.[¶](#appendix-A-3){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#future-handling-of-some-streams-created-by-nonconforming-encoders}
::: {#appendix-B .section}
## [Appendix B.](#appendix-B){.section-number .selfRef} [Future Handling of Some Streams Created by Nonconforming Encoders](#name-future-handling-of-some-str){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-future-handling-of-some-str}

This appendix is informative.[¶](#appendix-B-1){.pilcrow}

Some bitstreams were found with 40 extra bits corresponding to
`error_status` and `slice_crc_parity` in the `reserved` bits of `Slice`.
Any revision of this specification should avoid adding 40 bits of
content after `SliceContent` if `version == 0` or `version == 1`,
otherwise a decoder conforming to the revised specification could not
distinguish between a revised bitstream and such buggy bitstream in the
wild.[¶](#appendix-B-2){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

::: {#ffv1-implementations}
::: {#appendix-C .section}
## [Appendix C.](#appendix-C){.section-number .selfRef} [FFV1 Implementations](#name-ffv1-implementations){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-ffv1-implementations}

This appendix provides references to a few notable implementations of
FFV1.[¶](#appendix-C-1){.pilcrow}

::: {#ffmpeg-ffv1-codec}
::: {#appendix-C.1 .section}
### [C.1.](#appendix-C.1){.section-number .selfRef} [FFmpeg FFV1 Codec](#name-ffmpeg-ffv1-codec){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-ffmpeg-ffv1-codec}

This reference implementation \[[REFIMPL](#REFIMPL){.xref}\] contains no
known buffer overflow or cases where a specially crafted packet or video
segment could cause a significant increase in CPU
load.[¶](#appendix-C.1-1){.pilcrow}

The reference implementation \[[REFIMPL](#REFIMPL){.xref}\] was
validated in the following conditions:[¶](#appendix-C.1-2){.pilcrow}

-   [Sending the decoder valid packets generated by the reference
    encoder and verifying that the decoder\'s output matches the
    encoder\'s
    input.[¶](#appendix-C.1-3.1){.pilcrow}]{#appendix-C.1-3.1}
-   [Sending the decoder packets generated by the reference encoder and
    then subjected to random
    corruption.[¶](#appendix-C.1-3.2){.pilcrow}]{#appendix-C.1-3.2}
-   [Sending the decoder random packets that are not
    FFV1.[¶](#appendix-C.1-3.3){.pilcrow}]{#appendix-C.1-3.3}

In all of the conditions above, the decoder and encoder was run inside
the Valgrind memory debugger \[[Valgrind](#Valgrind){.xref}\] as well as
the Clang AddressSanitizer
\[[AddressSanitizer](#AddressSanitizer){.xref}\], which tracks reads and
writes to invalid memory regions as well as the use of uninitialized
memory. There were no errors reported on any of the tested
conditions.[¶](#appendix-C.1-4){.pilcrow}
:::
:::

An FFV1 decoder \[[FFV1GO](#FFV1GO){.xref}\] was written in Go by Derek

### [C.3.](#appendix-C.3){.section-number .selfRef} [MediaConch](#name-mediaconch){.section-name .selfRef} {#name-mediaconch}

The developers of the MediaConch project
\[[MediaConch](#MediaConch){.xref}\] created an independent FFV1 decoder
as part of that project to validate FFV1 bitstreams. This work led to
the discovery of three conflicts between existing FFV1 implementations
and draft versions of this document. These issues are addressed by
[Section 3.3.1](#exception){.xref}, [Section
3.7.2.1](#rgb-exception){.xref}, and [Appendix
B](#future-handling-of-some-streams-created-by-nonconforming-encoders){.xref}.[¶](#appendix-C.3-1){.pilcrow}
